text:
Eric predicts that #Cardano will fall out of the top 10.

He is wrong as he has been several times in the past. This prediction makes no sense.

He predicted it already in 2021. 

The Shelley hard fork brought staking to Cardano in 2020. Since then, the number of stakers has grown. 

Today there are 1.33M of stakers.

Cardano has liquid staking and is therefore considered a leader in this area.

The Alonzo hard fork brought smart contracts to Cardano in 2021. In 2022, the first applications began to appear.

In autumn 2022, Cardano got more efficient smart contracts thanks to the Vasil upgrade. Plutus V2 smart contracts are booming.

In 2023, Erik again predicts that Cardano will drop out of the top 10.

At the beginning of 2023, TVL started to grow significantly. This is still true today.

Staking $ADA is very popular. DeFi on Cardano is just getting started and has been successful so far.

Catalyst, Voltaire, other upgrades, USD-backed stablecoin, and other things will very likely keep Cardano where it is or move it higher.

Although we have little information about the PartnerChain Framework, we may see at least an announcement, if not a release, this year. 

This will bring Cardano closer to projects like Polkadot or Cosmos.

My guess is that we will see new partner chains sometime in 2025/26.

What I see is the growing interest of people in Cardano. 

New teams are coming that want to build applications on Cardano. 

They can develop new applications not only in Plutus but also in Aiken and several other languages.

I see progress on many fronts.

I see no reason why Cardano should drop out of the top 10 in 2024.

text:
#OpenSource Ethos üîì

#Cardano $ADA family! We are proud to officially announce that we will be open-sourcing the smart contracts used in the Genius Yield Dex!

A smart contract is a self-executing agreement with terms between the buyer and seller written into code.
Detailsüëá

üëâ Currently, our DEX uses a single order type: limit orders that can be partially filled, and market orders. These limit orders are created using a smart contract that ensures users' money is safe. The smart contract guarantees that the assets are locked in and only released if the user cancels the order or if a buyer pays the correct price. This smart contract defines the "rules of the game," and each time a user places an order, they entrust their assets to this smart contract.

üìñ Therefore, making the source code of that smart contract available is imperative. If we expect users to entrust the smart contract with their money without being able to see it, it's akin to asking someone to sign a contract without allowing them to read it first. For technical reasons, to keep track of the "life cycle" of an order on our DEX, we also deploy special NFTs. For each order, there is an NFT minted when the order is created and burnt when the order is completely filled or canceled. These NFTs are defined by a "minting policy" (another smart contract), which is carefully coordinated with the main order smart contract. We are open-sourcing both the order "validator" smart contract and the NFT "minting policy" smart contract.

üßê While both of these smart contracts have undergone audits in the past, we made changes during the testnet. Therefore, both of these smart contracts are undergoing a second audit. At the end of these audits, we will open-source the contracts under license.

Thank you for your support! Together we are building Cardano. ‚ù§ ü§ù

text:
Circle can freeze your $USDC account because it has control over the smart contract deployed on #Ethereum.

#Cardano has native assets.

It is not possible for a third party to have control over the assets in your Cardano wallet.

I will explain how Cardano tokens differ from tokens on other platforms.

First, it is necessary to understand what native assets are.

$ADA is a native asset like $ETH or $BTC. 

Cardano provides these functions for native coins.

- Storing coins in a ledger.
- Transferring coins between users.
- The ability to use coins in apps (DeFi).

Monetary policy, project treasury, and gradual release of ADA coins from circulation are rules implemented directly in the protocol.

The IOG team has no control over rules, transactions, or DeFi, as the Cardano network is composed of participants running nodes.

It is not possible to freeze an account (addresses) with ADA coins or prevent the spending of coins, as this is not implemented in the Cardano protocol. 

It is not possible to add malicious code to the protocol.

ADA coin is an asset that no one can confiscate. 

Transactions and storage of ADA in the ledger are the most secure operations as they are secured by the protocol code.

This code was delivered by the IOG team. It is the most tested functionality in Cardano as thousands of users use it daily.

See Figure 1.

Why shouldn't tokens have the same characteristics as ADA coins? 

Is there a use case where it makes sense for a third party to retain control over the tokens you have in your own wallet?

Cardano handles tokens just like ADA coins. With one difference.

Everyone has the opportunity to mint tokens on Cardano. The third party has control over the name of the token, the number of tokens, and the monetary policy (and a few other things).

The third party will decide whether to mint a certain number of tokens once and the number of tokens will never change, or whether it will be possible to burn tokens or mint new ones.

The third party may be an entity minting stablecoins. 

The bank holds the fiat currency and the third party mints (and burns) the tokens at a 1:1 ratio. In this case, the third party must retain control of the ability to mint and burn tokens forever.

In the case of minting NFT series, control over the ability to mint new NFTs in the series can be relinquished. It can be ensured that the amount of NFTs will never increase.

The token issuer has control only over the minting policy, i.e. the basic properties of tokens.

Cardano is fully responsible for the storage and transfer of tokens. These are features over which the token issuer has no control by design.

Control over monetary policy is separated from token ownership.

See Figure 2.

Cardano treats tokens natively. That is, just like ADA coins.

The token issuer can burn tokens only if the user sends them to his address. If the user has tokens at his address (in his wallet), it is not possible to burn the tokens.

Why is it possible to freeze an account with USDC (and USDT) tokens or blacklist addresses on Ethereum, but also on #Avalanche, #Solana, #Algorand, Near, #Polkadot, and other platforms?

Because tokens are issued via a smart contract. Protocols do not handle tokens natively.

Let's focus on Ethereum.

A token issuer on Ethereum must write a smart contract that defines all functionality related to tokens. 

Tokens are not only minted but also managed by smart contracts.

The most common token standards, such as ERC-20, define a set of functions for interacting with the tokens, including transferring tokens and querying the balance of an address.

The Ethereum protocol itself doesn‚Äôt directly manage tokens. Instead, it has an Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) that allows smart contracts to be executed.

See Figure 3.

Without EVM, Ethereum could not mint, transfer, or store tokens.

When a token is minted, the smart contract records the quantity of the token and assigns it to an Ethereum address.

Each Ethereum address that interacts with the token has an associated balance, which is stored in the smart contract‚Äôs state. 

When a token is transferred, the contract updates the state to reflect the new balances. 

The transfer function is a part of the smart contract that allows tokens to be sent from one address to another.

Through a smart contract, it is possible for a third party (such as Circle) to retain control of the tokens forever. 

It is possible to insert a code into the smart contract that will limit the rights of users.

See Figure 4.

It is fair to say that it is possible to write such a smart contract where the third party does not retain control of the tokens.

The problem is that if a regulated financial entity decides to use blockchain, it will write smart contracts in such a way that they comply with regulations (KYC & AML).

Simply put, Ethereum is regulatory-friendly while Cardano is not.

Those who care about preserving all the principles of decentralization and do not want to allow censorship of transactions will love Cardano.

On the other hand, it is easier for regulated financial institutions to use Ethereum (and other similar platforms) as it is possible to build an infrastructure that will comply with regulations.

Circle may not want to mint USDC as native tokens on Cardano. Native assets may be one of the main reasons why there is still no USD-backed stablecoin on Cardano.

Cardano is not regulatory compliant. This is good for users, but it can slow down adoption.

If decentralization is to win, then with all the principles that are important. 

Censoring transactions is against the interests of users. There is no reason to be regulatory compliant.

It is necessary to fight the current financial system at the level of the source code and enforce such functioning that will be beneficial for users, not institutions.

Regulators must adapt to the principles of decentralization, not the other way around.

It makes sense to keep Cardano as it is.

Cardano is built to comply with the principles of decentralization. 

The design of the native assets feature is great and must be maintained.

Changing the protocol to have $USDC doesn't make sense. 

#Cardano must not adapt to the requirements of companies, regulators, and states. Cardano needs to remain as the community wants it to be.

If the USDC is to be on Cardano, then:

- Circle accepts that Cardano has native assets.
- A different standard for tokens is implemented. Cardano will be more universal.
- We will only use bridged USDC (WanChain).

I would like to see USDC on Cardano. However, USDC is not a unique project. There are other ways to have USD-backed stablecoin.

If Mehen $USDM can be launched, we won't need USDC. It will be a missed business opportunity for Circle.

üì¢  Genius Yield Accelerated Yield Event! üì¢
#Cardano $ADA
ü•≥ We‚Äôre excited to announce the launch of our limited-time yield farm program, "Accelerated Yield." For a limited time, users will be able to earn boosted yield farming rewards by using the Genius Yield #DEX .

TL;DR:üëá

üìÖ From January 15th to February 15th, we will be rewarding traders based on how much they utilize our DEX. ‚òù Remember, for orders placed on our DEX, your ADA stays delegated to your stake pool, and you retain your voting rights in Catalyst.

The program has Two Tiers:

üèÜTier 1: 50,000 $GENS per week split among all traders on our DEX proportional to filled $ADA volume.

üèÜTier 2: For power users üí™ . If you traded at least 12,000 ADA in filled trades in each promotional weekly period, you will receive an additional 20% of DEX fees. Note that if you are staking $GENS, you are already eligible to receive 20% of DEX fees, meaning these users will be getting 40% of the DEX fees! üöÄ

ü§î Who is Eligible?
Tier 1: Anyone who placed an order on the Genius Yield‚Äôs DEX that was partially or completely filled during the promotional period.
Tier 2: Anyone who traded at least 12,000 ADA in filled trades in each promotional week and had at least 100 $GENS locked in the Genius Yield Staking Program by the end of each promotional week.
Find the App here: https://t.co/4IZVRqRAMm

ü§î How will I collect my rewards?
You will be able to claim the rewards at the Genius Yield app with the wallet address that conducted the trades. Rewards will be available for claiming every week, starting at the end of January/beginning of February 2024. The exact date will be announced soon!

ü§î When will Accelerated Yield rewards start?
The program starts on January 15th, 2024, 12:00 UTC, and will end on February 12th, 2024, 11:59 UTC. During this period, rewards will be accrued to all eligible traders.

Happy trading !! 
For more info, check out our Medium blog!

quote.text:
USDC On Cardano.

It's time.

I'm assembling a team.

In this post I'm going to explain why USDC on Cardano is a good thing, what I'm thinking of doing about it, and how you can help.

Please Like & Share for the entire community to see.

Firstly, I adamantly believe that USDC should be implemented on Cardano. There's debate around this, and we should always keep healthy debate going.

But in my view this move would supercharge Cardano for the following reasons:

1. Wider adoption - Cardano technology is special. It's been a consistent top 10 over many years, but it's now time for an easy onramp for the masses to discover this.

2. Interoperability & Efficiency - A simple connection, bridging Cardano to other ecosystems and financial systems.

3. Increased Use Cases - DeFi on Cardano is already loaded with innovation, but integrating USDC will increase the velocity in which these innovations come to existence and the ease in which they are experienced by the masses.

4. Market Confidence - The addition of a reputable asset like USDC and the implementation by Circle can increase market confidence in Cardano. A more robust and trusted ecosystem will simply attract more traders and investors, contributing to liquidity.

I know that many argue that this would make Cardano decentralized, but I want to propose to you that if we‚Äôre able to pull this off, this may be the exact event that actually brings decentralization to Cardano!

This could be a monumental turning point.

Here's why:

Circle requires a fee to implement USDC and there's a lot involved. Therefore many people are hounding CH to just get it done. I 100% disagree with this approach of trying to get CH or IOG to do this. I understand the thought, but it‚Äôs time to think about this differently.

Could you imagine how huge of a deal it would be if the COMMUNITY were to be the ones responsible for onboarding USDC onto Cardano?

This would not only be massive crypto news, but would be a crucial step in the direction of decentralization for Cardano.

The vehicle to do this has been built. I think this vehicle is Catalyst.

I'm a firm believer that if there‚Äôs a problem or challenge, it‚Äôs necessary to try and come up with the solution. Don't just keep talking about the problem. Be a part of the solution and get things done.

Will you support an endeavor to get this done?

text:
Meet the new crypto narrative:

"If the blockchain does not have a high TPS right now, then it has already lost and will disappear."

The #Cardano road map had clearly defined priorities from the very beginning.

First of all, the focus will be on decentralization. Then on scalability and governance.

This order is important:

‚û°Ô∏èThe blockchain industry is primarily about decentralization, not scalability.
‚û°Ô∏è It is technically difficult to further decentralize a running (scalable) network.
‚û°Ô∏è If the network is well decentralized, enough distributed computing resources (CPUs, memory, etc.) are available that can be used for scalability.

First of all, it must be said that Cardano scales well enough. There is no point in having 100K TPS if there is no demand.

The crypto industry is still in the HODL era. 

Crypto is not mainstream. Banks and institutions are preparing for HODL, not yet an economy running on public blockchains.

Cardano blocks are often full, so Cardano is at the edge of its throughput capacity.

The short-term solutions are:

‚û°Ô∏è Users must use Plutus V2 applications.
‚û°Ô∏è Teams responsible for Plutus V1 applications must migrate to Plutus V2 applications.
‚û°Ô∏è The team can increase the block size (or decrease the block time).

There are also a few long-term solutions:

‚û°Ô∏è Input Endorsers
‚û°Ô∏è Milkomeda
‚û°Ô∏è Hydra
‚û°Ô∏è Sidechains
‚û°Ô∏è Partner chains & Midnight
‚û°Ô∏è ZK rollups

A typical FUD goes like this: 

Cardano doesn't scale. There are no L2s. Input Endorsers are far away. Who cares about Midnight?

I would like to see Cardano better prepared for 2025 when an influx of new users can be expected.

There is still time to prepare for it.

It's easy to jump on the TPS narrative. 

The networks are fast and the UX is amazing. Transactions are settled almost instantly and are cheap. 

This is exactly what users want. This can compete with the traditional financial world.

But if such a network is not decentralized, what has actually been created? Maybe a good FinTech company. Definitely not a suitable infrastructure for disrupting the financial sector.

The competition has something that Cardano does not have yet, so they try to present it as an advantage. It is fair. 

However, it is not fair in the context of decentralization.

Obsession and adherence to decentralization are essential. 

Once the TPS blockchain with minimal decentralization is established, decentralization may further decrease and only a few entities will hold the keys.

Without on-chain governance, such an infrastructure will be in the hands of teams, i.e. VC funds.

Decentralization first is the foundation for disruption.

The IOG team delivered the best PoS network in the crypto industry. Staking on Cardano is a standard that everyone, including the #Ethereum team, is now trying to copy.

It is even becoming apparent to everyone how advantageous the UTxO model is for scalability. 

The reality is that Cardano is the leader in decentralization and everyone knows it.

Once the Input Endorsers are delivered, Cardano will be the technology leader as it will not only be decentralized but also scalable. Both at the same time.

There will be a few blockchains that are alike.

We can ask many questions: When will the Input Endorsers be delivered? When will we learn more about Partner Chains? When will Hydra be ready? When will the Midnight main-net launch?

The important thing is that everything is worked hard. 

It is important for Cardano not to get into TPS races and compromise on decentralization. It is important to build the infrastructure with the same care as before.

Scalability is essential for the adoption of blockchain technologies. However, decentralization and security are more important.

People don't care much about decentralization and if they see great UX, they just like it. It is important to keep going back to the roots of the crypto industry.

text:
I rarely see such a mix of nonsense, lies, and stupidity in one place.

Let's look at Cardano from a different perspective.

Ownership of Genesis keys will not allow the 3 founding entities to steal the funds of users or stop #Cardano. 

It's just a mechanism to allow for easy network upgrades in the early stages of development.

Genesis keys will be burned. Cardano will be fully owned by $ADA holders. 

This will make it more decentralized than, for example, #Bitcoin, as the team will not be in a position to make decisions.

ADA holders will decide about Cardano. 

From the on-chain analysis, it is easy to see that the number of wallets, stakers, and TVLs is growing. 

Cardano broke into the top 10 by TVL at the end of 2023.

I see growth. I don't know where Duo Nine is looking. People can leave but more of them are coming.

If you look at Catalyst, you will find that the interest in building on Cardano is huge.

A few weeks ago, the Genius Yiled and Lagon projects were launched. Axo will be launched this month. I'm only talking about bigger projects that just came to my mind.

These are not copy/paste projects. These projects bring new things and quality.

Aiken makes developing on Cardano much easier and is the preferred choice for developers. However, Plutus is still used. In addition, Marlowe is slowly getting going.

There are other alternatives besides Aiken. Aiken and other alternatives like Helios or Eopsin are not from IOG, Emurgo, or Cardano Foundation. They are community projects.

Has there been an alternative programming language built by the community on #Ethereum that would be more successful than Solidity?

Aiken is proof of success and interest.

Cardano as a platform is still in the early stages of development.

Cardano has been under construction since 2015, but this year marks only its third year as an SC platform.

Terra Luna was on the market faster than Cardano, but it's gone forever. Why? Because it was not a project that had such high ambitions as Cardano.

Cardano is being built much like software for NASA, hospitals, or nuclear power plants. The reason is simple. Users must never lose assets.

Last year there was a DeFi hack almost every 3 days. 

No Cardano's application has ever been hacked. This is no accident. This is proof that a scientific approach and careful slow development make sense.

Of course, it's also about the quality of third-party developers. It turns out that these are mostly professionals and not garage companies.

Criticizing the scientific approach and formal methods is a sign of misunderstanding Cardano's mission and difference from other VC projects.

Cardano is not Terra Luna or Solana. It's a different project with a different mission.

Cardano is to be a global financial and social operating system. There must not be numerous hacks. 100% uptime must be ensured.

It's easy to see why VC funds don't like Cardano. Because they couldn't buy ADA coins cheaply in the beginning. VC funds were not invited to the initial public ADA coin sale.

Paima Studio and others build ZK rollups. Cardano will have Hydra in the foreseeable future.

CoinBureau's video was very bad. Duo Nine's tweet is one level worse pile of nonsense.

Cardano does not have to compete with other blockchains and can develop at its own pace.

The interest of VC funds and even the current market capitalization is not important. 

If Cardano succeeds technologically in the long term and continues to have a growing community, it will be among the top 3 projects and the market capitalization will reflect that.

It's easy to find negatives and take them to the extreme. It's more difficult to do your own research and see Cardano in a wider context. This is where CoinBureau failed, as well as Duo Nine.

Some final facts:

- Cardano is undeniably the most decentralized network in the top 10 in block production.
- Cardano will be in the hands of the community and it will determine the priorities.
- Cardano has been in the top 10 since 2017. The project survived 2 bear markets.
- The Cardano community is in the top 3 by engagement.
- Scientific approach and formal methods are used for software development in all globally successful companies and for mission-critical infrastructure.

üö®  Cardano fanboys have no clue that ADA is just a VC coin! They will yell & disagree, but the facts remain. 

ADA is owned by three entities holding the genesis key: 

üî∏ Cardano Foundation
üî∏ Emurgo
üî∏ IOG

That's why the SEC called it a security. The last two are VCs that raised the money for ADA.

A total of $62 mil was raised in various ICOs between 2015-2017, and in late 2017 ADA chain was launched. 

Cardano never took off due to lack of adoption. Developers and projects are leaving their ecosystem because "it's hard to build" on Cardano. 

Those that stay are usually bought or paid by the above three entities. This comes at your expense since they sell ADA to finance their costs.

‚ö†Ô∏è  Here's a key question to enlighten you. 

Why does Tron (lol) have native USDC and USDT on its network, but Cardano does not after almost eight years since it went live?

Tron network is seeing TRILLIONS in stablecoin transfer volume per year. 

ADA? 20 mil in stablecoin mcap.  ü§£

I could stop this post right here, but there's so much more to cover!

Cardano is number 10 in terms of DeFi TVL at $368 mil, much of it thanks to ADA's recent price pump. 

That's 0.37 bil out of a 53 bil DeFi market or 0.7%. That's not even 1% after eight years of development!

Do you now understand why developers are leaving?  

This slow adoption, if we can even call it that, is blamed on Charles - the ADA CEO - due to his time-consuming "academic approach". 

He cashed-in big after leaving ETH early on and then built his own chain now known as ADA. He cashed-in big again. lol

While ETH went out and broke things to grow, ADA published research papers. Seriously - no joke.  ü§Ø

This is why ADA has many fanboys. Because they say it's "superior". Guess they never heard of meme coins that saw more adoption.

This lack of adoption is why Cardano is now FULL ON revising their governance system to "decentralize". 

Their latest update is called Voltaire or Cardano Improvement Plan (CIP) 1694. Note the word "revise" used in their documents.

You must understand that those VCs have every interest to farm this for as long as possible. 

After eight years, they need to do something, else more money will leave their chain for good.

The best part about the Voltaire update? 

It will have a "constitutional committee" that will likely consist of the current genesis key holders at first: Cardano Foundation + Emurgo + IOG. 

Funny how that works, right?

Charles says their keys will be destroyed as new members will displace current incumbents.

A "constitutional committee" was not on my decentralization bingo card this year. But it fixes one big problem for Charles.

Cardano is no longer a security! 

Charles says CIP 1694 makes it irrelevant who holds the keys. I say it just obfuscates more the truth and reads like an exit for the VCs.  

eToro, Robinhood, and Revolut delisted Cardano in the past. 

VCs know they are on borrowed time to "decentralize" or exit. Once the community takes over, they won't care anyway. 

Right now, all efforts are on "decentralization" or CIP 1694 while Cardano's adoption continues to suffer in the midst of a new bull market. 

By the time the VCs exit, the community will not be left with much but a ghost chain with an inflated market cap thanks to its 45 billion tokens.

There are no independent Layer-2 solutions on Cardano. Why? 

Because Cardano does not need to scale. What's there to scale? 

The L2s that exist (Hydra + Mithril) are both developed by... wait for it... IOG or Charles. See the problem?

The most striking part of all this is how little Cardano has integrated with the rest of the crypto space. 

It's an abandoned island in the middle of the Pacific ruled by three entities and Charles as its king. Basically a security, remember?

Even Tron did better which already says a lot since that's a one man show without much interest in "research" or "papers". 

If this is news to you, then you haven't seen Coin Bureau's latest video about Cardano which inspired this post.

Those are some hard truth pills to swallow.

Hit a follow @du09btc, join my discord, subscribe to my newsletter for similar content, all links in bio.

P.S. I respect the ADA community and this is not intended as FUD. But please wake up. Don't marry your bags.

text:
A few things, #Cardano is the most decentralized major L1 in crypto as measured by block production, and has been for awhile. It's TVL went up in the bear market before $ADA pumped, organically, despite not having a fiat stable, while others mostly flatlined. 

It had one of the more fair coin distributions, especially compared to the VC chains and is similar to ETH in this regard. In fact, data shows it is dispersing more equitably as time goes on, unlike most others. 

Regarding not "integrating" with the rest of the space. Most of the rest of the space are Ethereum clones based around account based models or worse, like proof of history with solana, they are, riddled with hacks, high costs, and questionable uptime, tokenomics and more, they're extractive at best. eutxo is very different by it's very nature. It's an actual alternative where as most of the others are not, they merely permutations of the same account system or worse.

Now define "adoption". Is it processing USDT like tron? A centralized token that can be frozen at will? hardly an achievement considering crypto's original goals across the industry. Is the goal to be the most decentralized, have the strongest security, highest uptime, and the most engaged community in crypto building organically, to have a foundation worthy of building on? Well by that measure Cardano does great. Surely, given your distaste for the VC coins, which outside of ETH, are the only real competition, it isn't the falsified metrics and wash/bot trading, right? I would hope so.

Cardano is the only major layer 1 going after real genuine on chain governance, which has never been done before, robustly. Cardano isn't "revising" it's governance process, it's literally forming it in the first place. The CIP nomenclature follows the same tradition as BIP and EIP. To suggest otherwise is disingenuous. Now you can suggest or at least intimate that that @IOHK_Charles  is lying when he says CIP 1694 makes it irrelevant who holds the keys. That's an opinion, not a presentation of data or evidence. We will know when it's finally implemented and as time moves on. 

Charles is already a billionaire without Cardano, he doesn't need to "rug" Cardano. You can claim of course, he is pushing voltaire to not be labeled a security, but a claim has to be backed up with evidence to be more than just an opinion. But if you look at the roadmap, on chain governance was part of the roadmap going back at Cardano's inception. 

Most of the ecosystem growth has come from the community. Cardano also has the highest github dev activity in the industry. If you aren't aware of what's going on, one example is @IagonOfficial, who left Ethereum specifically to come to Cardano for it's cheap predictable fees, high security, uptime, and community support, and with midnight, which is a privacy sidechain allowing for easy to implement ZK rollups for data sensitive material. That is what web2 enterprises, new outside liquidity and money, care about. Security and reliability. That's the feedback they give.

$IAG in just a week of launching has 3x the nodes as arweave, a competitor, and is more distributed than AWS, with 30 different countries hosting nodes to share storage resources, with compute coming in Q1. No chain is perfect, but Cardano's actual fundamentals are quite strong. I can only fit 4 images in this post, or I would share more.  

Your source, guy from coin bureau video, has even admitted after getting feedback that he didn't really dig into nor discuss all the stuff outlined here, and should have done so, but time didn't permit it.

text:
The ultimate metaverse experience arrived on the Blockchain!
 
With the token $COPI that did a 3X in the last months, I present you @CornucopiasGame!
 
A world with no boundaries with a player-driven economy being built on #Cardano!

The level of ambition is the highest I‚Äôve ever seen for a game.

But right now the game is still in its initial phase of development and you‚Äôll need an NFT to access this early build.

That will allow you to:
 
- Explore the city
- Participate in races

The Early Stages of Cornucopias

The city is already huge. 

Just to get to the race track it will take you a few minutes by catching the subway.
 
Everything in Cornucopias is like in real life. 

When you‚Äôre on the subway you have to wait and you‚Äôll need to know on which stop to exit.

After you get to the race track the real fun begins. 

You‚Äôll race with a ship and if you hit the edges of the race it might explode.

The game does a great job of giving you a feeling of speed and it requires skill to control your vehicle.

Upcoming features

The team is working 24/7 to bring new features to the current build, like:

- Crafting
- Quests
-  Mounts
-  Flying vehicles
-  Floating home
-  NFT land in the form of costume domes

Players will also be able to build their own experiences through the building kits that the team will develop.

So imagine The Sandbox experiences but with UE5 graphics.

COPI

This ecosystem is powered by the token $COPI which exists in the BNB Smart chain and Cardano.

The token will have the following utility:

You can also buy a file node license and get rewarded with tokens.
 
File nodes will break the game into multiple chunks and players will download it directly from the nodes.

NFTs

NFTs in Cornucopias will exist in many forms:
 
- Vehicles
- Land
- Dome
- Trees
- Bobblehead
- Racer suits

And more to come.

Overall

Cornucopias is a highly ambitious project. The team really aims to build a world with no boundaries.

Imagine something like Star Citizen but powered by the blockchain.

We‚Äôre still in our early days but we can already see the massive scope of this game with its current build.

You can already get lost and spend hours exploring the city.

Personally, I am excited and can‚Äôt wait for what‚Äôs to come for Cornucopias.

text:
Coinbureau's Cardano Update video is shallow and incomplete. I miss the bigger picture the most.

#Cardano, as well as many other projects, are complex projects with large ecosystems. It is difficult to overcome the entry barrier and penetrate the depth of projects. 

It is even more difficult to compare projects with each other and form an opinion on future potential.

I appreciate that CoinBureau is not ignoring Cardano and that it is not being paid for negative reporting. I think he was trying to be objective.

When he talked about the so-called "shut down", he should have said that there was an automatic recovery of all affected nodes and the network was healthy in a short time. The result of the message was supposed to be proof that Cardano is a robust network.

There are more similar inaccurate messages out there without wider context.

Personally, I would like it if influencers talked more about what is important for crypto. 

For example, decentralization, scalability, about what ordinary people expect and want from crypto. They should focus more on developing technologies that will enable adoption. This can be tricky.

25 minutes is a short time to make a video about Cardano Update. 

In such a short time, it is not possible to include, for example, Mithril in the update. I find it essential to mention Input Endorsers in the context of #Ethereum leaving L1 scalability. I could go on.

What to take away from this? Even influencers trying for objective reporting are not able to penetrate into the depth of projects and get a broader picture.

https://t.co/toX0soJBmZ
